title.narrative: WASH ENABLING ENVIRONMENT

description.narrative: By 2023, national and sub-national authorities have strengthened capacity to plan, coordinate, and monitor inclusive, quality, child focused Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) services to communities and institutions (schools and health care facilities), including in emergencies., which contributes to Climate Change, Disaster Risks And Envionmental Degradation, Reducing Child Poverty, Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices, Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Systems And Empowerment Of Communities. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Partnerships And Engagement: Public And Private, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023, underserved children equitably use safe water and practise safe sanitation and hygiene, including during humanitarian situations.

description.narrative: UNICEFsupported the national and sub-national WASH sector systems strengthening activities and updated the national reporting to global level on WASH SDG goals among continued COVID restrictions. National and sub-national sector coordination was enhanced, and capacity developed in climate related risk informed programming. Technical support given to formulate state rural WASH budget. Anofficewide climate change action plan was developed; a climate resilient WASH formative evaluation initiated, and a benchmarking paper was drafted. UNICEF reported into Cambodia’s Nationally Determined Contribution coordination mechanism. Material and technical support provided to national COVID related WASH responses and emergency flood preparedness in 6 provinces. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:10/01/2022
